<h2>HVAC Systems in Missouri</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Missouri's continental climate presents unique challenges for HVAC systems, requiring equipment capable of handling both extreme heat and bitter cold. Summer temperatures regularly reach the upper 80s to mid-90s¬∞F with high humidity levels, creating substantial cooling loads that can strain inefficient air conditioning systems. The state experiences an average of 35-45 days per year with temperatures above 90¬∞F, with the hottest regions in southern Missouri seeing even more extreme conditions. Heat index values frequently exceed 100¬∞F during peak summer months, making reliable air conditioning essential for comfort and health.</p>

<p>Winter conditions are equally demanding, with average low temperatures ranging from the teens in northern Missouri to the mid-20s in the south. The state typically experiences 120-150 heating degree days annually, requiring robust heating systems capable of maintaining comfortable indoor temperatures during extended cold periods. Snow and ice storms can impact system performance and create additional heating demands, while spring and fall weather can be highly variable, requiring HVAC systems that can efficiently transition between heating and cooling modes.</p>

<p>Humidity control represents another critical consideration for Missouri HVAC systems. Summer humidity levels often exceed 70%, creating comfort issues and potential indoor air quality problems if not properly managed. Effective dehumidification not only improves comfort but also helps prevent mold and mildew growth, protects indoor furnishings, and can actually allow homeowners to set thermostats at slightly higher temperatures while maintaining comfort. Modern HVAC systems with variable-speed components and enhanced dehumidification capabilities are particularly well-suited for Missouri's climate challenges.</p>

